                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="12481769" author="kmarsden" created="Fri, 16 Mar 2007 21:46:28 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Attached patch adds RuntimeStatisticsParser.java to  parse isolation out of Runtime statistics.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;JDBC.getRuntimeStatisticsParser(Statement s) method to return the parser to the test.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;RuntimeStatisticsParserTest tests the functionality.  I put that right in the junit directory but am not sure if that is the right  place for it.&lt;/p&gt;

</comment>
                            <comment id="12481774" author="djd" created="Fri, 16 Mar 2007 22:35:53 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I would say that this is not a utility for JDBC, but instead some utility for SQL language.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As for a test for the test code, not sure about that. &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/smile.gif&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt; We don&apos;t have tests for the other test methods, such as assertFullResultSet(), so why would we need tests for this utility? And then how far do we go, do we need a test for RuntimeStatisticsParserTest ? &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/smile.gif&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12481777" author="mkhettry" created="Fri, 16 Mar 2007 22:46:47 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;These questions may be silly but here goes&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1. Is it possible that the RuntimeStatisticsParser constructor can be called with a null value for rts?&lt;br/&gt;
2. Since the procedure SYSCS_UTIL.SYSCS_GET_RUNTIMESTATISTICS() returns a RuntimeStatistics object it seems a shame to convert this object to a string and then parse it. Is it possible to manipulate this object directly?&lt;br/&gt;
3. A common usage for something like this would be&lt;br/&gt;
  a. set runtime statistics on&lt;br/&gt;
  b. parse and possibly execute query. &lt;br/&gt;
  c. look at runtime stats.&lt;br/&gt;
It would be nice if there was a helper method to combine all these steps into one routine especially if the test does not care about results returned in 2.&lt;br/&gt;
4. It would be nice if we could extract other information from this parser, not just the isolation level!&lt;/p&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="12481789" author="kmarsden" created="Fri, 16 Mar 2007 23:39:25 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks Dan and Manish for the comments.&lt;br/&gt;
Dan, &lt;br/&gt;
&amp;gt;would say that this is not a utility for JDBC, but instead some utility for SQL language.&lt;br/&gt;
So a new class SQLUtilities.java  to provide a home for this?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;gt;As for a test for the test code, not sure about that. &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/smile.gif&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt; &lt;br/&gt;
I&apos;ll trash it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Manish&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;gt;1. Is it possible that the RuntimeStatisticsParser constructor can be called with a null value for rts?&lt;br/&gt;
I don&apos;t think so.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;gt;2. Since the procedure SYSCS_UTIL.SYSCS_GET_RUNTIMESTATISTICS() returns a &amp;gt;RuntimeStatistics object it seems a shame to convert this object to a string and then parse it. Is it &amp;gt;possible to manipulate this object directly?&lt;br/&gt;
I don&apos;t know how without java Object support&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;gt;3. A common usage for something like this would be&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;gt;  a. set runtime statistics on&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;gt;  b. parse and possibly execute query.&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;gt;  c. look at runtime stats.&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;gt;It would be nice if there was a helper method to combine all these steps into one routine especially if &amp;gt;the test does not care about results returned in 2.&lt;br/&gt;
That sounds like a good idea.  I&apos;ll add it as soon as I know where to put these methods.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;gt;4. It would be nice if we could extract other information from this parser, not just the isolation level!&lt;br/&gt;
Yes, this is just a start on the Parser.  It can be expanded as needed.  It would be good for it to mimic RunTimeStatistics.&lt;/p&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="12481916" author="knutanders" created="Sun, 18 Mar 2007 07:56:20 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The class definition in RunTimeStatisticsParser.java says RuntimeStatisticsParser (RunTime vs Runtime) so the patch doesn&apos;t compile on OSs where file names are case sensitive.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12482495" author="kmarsden" created="Tue, 20 Mar 2007 19:26:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Incorporate review comments&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12483641" author="kmarsden" created="Fri, 23 Mar 2007 15:54:50 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;committed initial patch for RuntimeStatisticsParser.  I will leave this open until other functionality is added.  I am unassigning myself as I don&apos;t plan to work on it  now.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12484151" author="army" created="Mon, 26 Mar 2007 17:27:01 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Just for reference: the work for &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/DERBY-2487&quot; title=&quot;Enhance Derby with EXPLAIN Functionality&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;DERBY-2487&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;DERBY-2487&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, once completed, may allow the RuntimeStatisticsParser to retrieve required information by executing queries against system tables, which seems a tad cleaner than trying to parse the current query plan string.  I don&apos;t know exactly how that will work just yet, but I thought I&apos;d include a pointer to the relevant Jira for tracking purposes...&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12646299" author="kmarsden" created="Mon, 10 Nov 2008 17:14:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Resolving this for now, since RuntimeStatisticsParser has been committed for some time and has been enhanced as part of other issues.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
